Ex 1.b Grouped summary statistics [2 points]

Use piping to perform the following steps on data_BLJM:

  1. throw out all rows where the column gender has an entry of NA (Hint: use function is.na and Boolean negation);
  2. group by gender
  3. obtain the mean and (unbiased) standard deviation for age (exluding NAs in both functions (see Ex 1.a))
data_BLJM %>% 
  filter(., !is.na(gender)) %>%
  group_by(gender) %>%
  summarise(
    age_mean = mean(age, na.rm = T),
    stddev_age = sd(age, na.rm = T), 
  )

data_BLJM_processed <-

Ex 1.f Plot the music+subject choices [2 points]

Create a plot for the current data set similar to that of Figure 5.1 from the web-book. Comment your code exetensivly, explaining each relevant step as if you were trying to teach somebody R and ggplot.

(Hint: you can recycle code from the web-book, but you need to find it.)

data_BLJM_conditions_select %>%
  ggplot(aes(
    # define x ...
    x = LB,
    # ... and y axis
    y = n,
    # use different colors for Jazz and Metal
    color = JM,
    # use different shapes for Jazz and Metal
    shape = JM,
    # we want to create points / lines for Jazz and Metal separately, not together
    group = JM
   )
  ) + 
  # plot the points with size 3
  geom_point(size = 3) +
  # create respective lines for Jazz and Metal
  geom_line() +
  # add labels describing plot
  labs(
    title = "Counts of responses of each music+subject pair", 
    x = "",
    y = ""
  )

Ex 1.g Interpret the plot [3 points]

Argue, if you can, that the lecturer’s conjecture is true: students who like metal also prefer logic, and vice versa. Or, if you must, argue that the the data does not provide (visual) evidence for the lecturer’s conjecture. (Make your answer short; at most four concise sentences, please!)

Answer

People who chose Logic chose more often Jazz than Metal. People who chose Metal chose more often Biology than Logic. As such, the data provides counter-evidence to the lecturer’s conjecture.

Exercise 2: Musings about modes [5 points]

Suppose we have a vector of metric data points, stemming from measurements of weight of around ten thousand seagulls. The weight has been determined up to the yoctogram level. (Just imagine that this was actually possible!) Why would it probably not make much good sense to consider the mode of this vector as an indicator of central tendency of these measurements?

Answer

As mentioned in the web book, the mode “is the unique value that occurred most frequently in the data”. Considering that we are measuring weights on a yoctogram level, even with data of ten thousand seagulls, it’s highly likely that no weight measurement will occur twice (in which case, there would be no mode) or that maybe a very small number of (like max. 10) seagulls have the same weight (let’s call that weight x) up to the yoctogram level. ( In the latter case, the mode is not a good measure of tendency since while the weight x would be the most frequent one, it is likely that just by random chance, x happened to be the mode in our specific data set, while it could have just as well been a (completely) different value if we sampled another 10000 seagull weights.

Ex 3.a Calculate a correlation score [2 points]

Use R’s built-in function cor to compute the Bravais-Pearson correlation between the variables FertilityRate and LifeExpectancy. Notice that you must first remove all entries in either column with missing data.

fr_and_le <- data_WHO %>% 
  # select only FertilityRate and LifeExpectancy
  select(FertilityRate, LifeExpectancy) %>%
  # filter out rows with na values
  filter(!(is.na(FertilityRate) | is.na(LifeExpectancy))) 

# compute correlation

Ex 3.b Interpret a correlation score [3 points]

Interpret this numerical result. Your answer be something like the following (but hopefully much better): “There appears to be a positive correlation between \(X\) and \(Y\) suggesting that as \(X\) increases \(Y\) will decrease. This is proof that \(X\) is a causally related to \(Y\), in fact that \(Y\) is the cause of \(X\).”

Answer

There appears to be a negative correlation between FertilityRate and LifeExpectancy. That is, with larger FertilityRate values, LifeExpectanty values become lower and vice versa.
However, this does not imply that the two are causally related.

Ex 3.c Compute correlation scores for each region [2 points]

Use R’s built-in function cor to compute the Bravais-Pearson correlation between the variables FertilityRate and LifeExpectancy seperately for each region. Use group_by and remember to remove missing values. Store the resulting tibble in a variable called correlation_WHO because we will use it later on.

correlation_WHO <- data_WHO %>% 
  # only select relevant variables
  select(Region, FertilityRate, LifeExpectancy) %>%
  # filter out rows with na values
  filter(!(is.na(FertilityRate) | is.na(LifeExpectancy))) %>%
  group_by(Region) %>%
  # add column for correlations
  mutate(correlation = cor(FertilityRate, LifeExpectancy)) %>%
  # remove duplicate region rows
  distinct(., Region, .keep_all = T)

correlation_WHO

Ex 3.d Make a scatter plot [3 points]

Create a scatterplot (using geom_point) showing FertilityRate on the \(x\)-axis and LifeExpectancy on the \(y\)-axis. Add a linear regression line, using geom_smooth. (Hint: See Section 6.3.3 of the web-book). For good sports, check the documentation of geom_smooth to find an option that suppresses the gray area around the regression line (which is a confidence interval; a concept we will learn about later in the course). Finally, adjust the axis labels, so as not to show CamelCaseLabels but “Nice labels with spaces”.

data_WHO %>% 
  ggplot(
    #map "FertilityRate" onto x-axis
    mapping = aes(x = FertilityRate, 
    #map "LifeExpectancy" onto y-axis             
                  y = LifeExpectancy))+
    #add a scatter plot
  geom_point()+
    #add a linear regression line
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", 
    #remove the confidence interval            
              se = FALSE)+
    #change axis labes
labs(x = 'Fertility rate', y = 'Life expectancy')

Ex 3.e Make a scatter plot facetted by region [2 points]

Use facet_wrap to make six nicely arranged scatter plots, one for each level of Region, of FertilityRate against LifeExpectancy (as before: with linear regression lines w/o confidence intervals and nice axis labels). Make sure that each facet has its own range of values shown for the \(x\)- and \(y\)-axis, using the scales option of facet_wrap.

facet <- data_WHO %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = FertilityRate, y = LifeExpectancy))+
  geom_point()+
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE)+
labs(x = 'Fertility rate', y = 'Life expectancy')+
  #arrange scatter plots one for each level of 'Region'
  facet_wrap(~Region, 
  #make each facet have its own range of values(make them free in one dimension)
             scales = "free")
facet
